        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>All International&#174; vehicles are designed to protect the exhaust aftertreatment system from
                    both heavy rainfall and water from truck washes through the use of water separation technologies.
                    This ensures that the catalyst and diesel particulate filter (DPF) are protected from outside water
                    for the life of the treatment system. The water separation system varies depending on the exhaust
                    and aftertreatment configuration, but they all include some form of drain hole that allows ingested
                    water to escape prior to reaching the internal components of the aftertreatment. This hole may be
                    located in the aftertreatment canister (Figure 2), the tailpipe (Figure 3), or the support stanchion
                    (Figure 4). The drain hole may be drilled, punched, or in some cases threaded. In each case as
                    explained, the hole is critical to the design and must be kept clean and open at all times. Under no
                    circumstances should this hole be plugged. NO TAILPIPE TURNOUT OR RAINCAP IS NEEDED FOR THIS SYSTEM.
                </para>
